    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Cuba Embargo: Desired Results?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Craig Watson letter on Sen Jesse Helms's June 24 article holds Cuba should be gradually led toward democracy by slow exposure to outside world</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re '''On Trade, Cuba Is Not China'' (Op-Ed, June 24):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re '''On Trade, Cuba Is Not China'' (Op-Ed, June 24):</p>
        <p>Jesse Helms argues that an end to the Cuba embargo will not bring about democratic changes in Cuba. But he overlooks the potential results of increased engagement with Cuba.</p>
        <p>Eventually, change will come to Cuba. When change does occur, which is preferable: a Cuban society gradually led toward democracy by slow exposure to the outside world, or one coping with the ill effects of sudden exposure to the global economy as seen elsewhere?</p>
        <p>CRAIG WATSON  Brooklyn, June 24, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
